seg.seg:
quin contra, uelut parens
                                indulgentissima optima quaeque in propatulo posuerit, ut aerem,
                                aquam ac tellurem ipsam;

Neque enim de felicitate
                                disceptant unquam, quin principia quaedam ex religione deprompta tum
                                phi­losophia quae rationibus utitur, coniungant;

Ex poetis habent
                                Aristophanem, Homerum atque Euripidem, tum Sophoclem minus­culis
                                Aldi formulis;

Tum quae ex ipsis
                                exportanda sint, ea consultius putant ab se efferri quam ab aliis
                                illinc peti;

For where as they eate and
                                drincke in earthen and glasse vesselles, which in dede be curiously
                                and properlie made, and yet be of very small value;

For they neuer dyspute of
                                felycytye or blessednes, but they ioyne to the reasons of
                                Philosophye certeyne pryncyples taken owte of relygyon;

For thoughe there be almost
                                no nation vnder heauen that hath lesse nede of Phisick then they,
                                yet, this notwithstandyng, Phisicke is no where in greater honour;
